.TH execute-file 2
.XI execute-file \- "\*(C0Execute script lines from a file"
.SH NAME
execute-file \- Execute script lines from a file
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.I n
.B execute-file
"\fIfile\fR" \*(C0
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B execute-file
executes script lines from the given  \fIfile\fR in succession,  this is the normal way to execute a \*(mE script. The
command prompts for a file name, and will then search for  <\fIfile\fR>[.emf] in the search path. If the file is found
then the file is loaded and the buffer is executed \fIn\fR times.
.PP
If numeric argument \fIn\fR is given then macro argument variable
.Ht @? 4
will be set to 1 and
.Ht @# 4
to \fIn\fR,  otherwise  \fB@?\fR and \fB@#\fR will be set to 0 and 1 respectively.  These variables can be used by the
macro code during the execution of the file.
